INSERT INTO `dissertations` (`dissertation_id`, `student_id`, `user_id`, `title`, `topic_area`, `program`, `program_type`, `academic_year`, `semester`, `year_of_study`, `status`, `current_phase`, `supervisor_id`, `co_supervisor_id`, `coordinator_id`, `concept_note_text`, `concept_note_file`, `topic_submitted_at`, `supervisor_assigned_at`, `proposal_approved_at`, `ethics_approved_at`, `defense_date`, `defense_grade`, `defense_result`, `completed_at`, `total_word_count`, `is_active`, `created_at`, `updated_at`) VALUES ('1', 'BBA/26/ODL/NE/0005', '55', 'Assessing the Impact of Taxpayers\' Money on Government Spending in Agriculture – The Case of Malawi', 'Account and Finance', 'Bachelor of Business Administration', 'degree', '2026', 'One', '4', 'chapter3_submitted', 'chapter3', '33', '29', NULL, '1. Introduction and Background\r\nMalawi\'s economy is heavily reliant on agriculture, which contributes approximately 22% to the country\'s Gross Domestic Product (GDP) and accounts for about 76% of total employment. The sector also generates around 85% of export earnings, with tobacco alone contributing over 40%. Despite this centrality, agricultural productivity remains low, with value added per worker below regional averages, exacerbated by climate vulnerabilities, limited infrastructure, and inefficiencies in public resource allocation.\r\nGovernment spending on agriculture has consistently met or exceeded the Comprehensive Africa Agriculture Development Programme (CAADP) target of 10% of the national budget, averaging 9.2% to 11.8% in recent years (e.g., 10.8% in 2022/23 and 11.8% in 2023/24). This funding is primarily sourced from taxpayer revenues, which constitute 67-86% of total government revenue, with tax-to-GDP ratios ranging from 12.5% to 13.5% between 2022 and 2023. Major tax sources include Value Added Tax (VAT) at 27-30% of tax revenues and corporate income taxes at 25%. In the 2024/25 fiscal year, the Malawi Revenue Authority collected MK3.06 trillion in taxes, representing 94% of the target and a 40% increase from the prior year.\r\nHowever, a significant portion of agricultural spending—often over 50%—has historically been directed toward input subsidies like the Affordable Inputs Programme (AIP), formerly the Farm Input Subsidy Programme (FISP), which accounted for up to 75% of the Ministry of Agriculture\'s budget around 2015. Recent reforms have reduced AIP\'s share to about 30-32% by targeting fewer beneficiaries (from 3.7 million to 1.1 million in 2024/25), freeing up resources for other areas. Despite these efforts, agricultural GDP growth has averaged below the CAADP\'s 6% target, registering only 0.8-0.9% in 2023/24 due to factors like El Niño-induced droughts.\r\nThis concept note proposes a study to evaluate how taxpayers\' contributions, channeled through government budgets, influence agricultural outcomes in Malawi, focusing on efficiency, productivity, and sustainability.\r\n2. Problem Statement\r\nWhile Malawi allocates substantial taxpayer-funded resources to agriculture—e.g., MK455.1 billion (11.8% of the 2023/24 national budget)—the sector\'s performance remains suboptimal. Over two-thirds of on-budget spending has gone to subsidies with low benefit-cost ratios (BCRs) of 1 or below, indicating inefficiency and limited impact on productivity. For instance, the AIP has increased welfare and provided food insurance but at high costs (MK178.4 billion in 2021/22), often crowding out investments in high-return areas like extension services (BCR 2.5), irrigation (potential 10% output increase), and research.\r\nExternal factors, including climate shocks and policy distortions (e.g., negative nominal rates of protection for key crops), further erode returns. Donor funding covers 54% of agricultural expenditures, but off-budget flows reduce government coordination. This misalignment raises questions about the value taxpayers receive, as persistent low growth (below 6%) perpetuates food insecurity and poverty for the rural majority.\r\n3. Objectives\r\nGeneral Objective\r\nTo assess the impact of taxpayer-funded government spending on agricultural productivity, growth, and sustainability in Malawi.\r\nSpecific Objectives\r\n\r\nTo analyze trends in taxpayer contributions to government revenue and their allocation to agriculture (2016-2025).\r\nTo evaluate the efficiency and returns of major spending categories (e.g., subsidies vs. public goods like irrigation and extension).\r\nTo identify barriers to effective spending and recommend reforms for better alignment with national goals like Malawi Vision 2063.\r\nTo quantify socioeconomic impacts, including on smallholder farmers\' incomes and food security.\r\n\r\n4. Rationale and Justification\r\nThis assessment is timely amid ongoing reforms, such as AIP targeting and increased focus on commercialization (e.g., via the Agricultural Productivity and Commercialization Programme, supported by a $16.94 million ADF grant). Evidence shows that reallocating from subsidies to public investments could yield higher BCRs (6.8-14.2 regionally for extension). With taxpayer revenues growing 40% in 2024/25 but compliance challenges persisting, understanding impacts can enhance accountability, inform budget decisions, and support sustainable growth. The study aligns with CAADP commitments and addresses gaps in existing reviews, such as the World Bank\'s Agriculture Public Expenditure Review.\r\n5. Methodology\r\nStudy Design\r\nA mixed-methods approach combining quantitative analysis (e.g., econometric modeling of spending impacts on GDP growth) with qualitative insights (e.g., stakeholder interviews).\r\nData Sources\r\n\r\nSecondary data: Government budgets, Malawi Revenue Authority reports, World Bank/IFPRI databases, and Agricultural Production Estimate Surveys.\r\nPrimary data: Surveys of 500 smallholder farmers and key informant interviews with Ministry of Agriculture officials, taxpayers, and donors.\r\n\r\nAnalytical Methods\r\n\r\nCost-Benefit Analysis (CBA) and Propensity Score Matching (PSM) to estimate BCRs for spending categories.\r\nVector Autoregression (VAR) models to assess causal links between public expenditure and productivity.\r\nThematic analysis for qualitative data.\r\n\r\nScope and Limitations\r\nFocus on 2016-2025, limited to central government spending; potential data gaps on off-budget flows may be addressed via donor consultations.\r\n6. Expected Outcomes and Impacts\r\n\r\nA comprehensive report with evidence-based recommendations for reallocating spending to high-impact areas (e.g., increasing extension funding from 16% government contribution to meet NAEASS targets).\r\nPolicy briefs for stakeholders, potentially influencing the 2026/27 budget to prioritize productivity-enhancing investments.\r\nEnhanced taxpayer awareness and government accountability, contributing to 6% agricultural growth and reduced poverty.', 'uploads/dissertations/concept_notes/concept_BBA_26_ODL_NE_0005_1772986314.docx', '2026-03-08 18:11:55', '2026-03-08 20:16:56', NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, '0', '1', '2026-03-08 18:11:55', '2026-03-11 01:41:10');
